\chapter{Genus of a smooth proper curve}
\label{chap:Genus}

Throughout this chapter, $k$ denotes a field and $C$ a smooth proper geometrically irreducible scheme over $k$ of relative dimension $1$ — that is, $C \to \Spec k$ carries the typeclasses
\lstinline{[SmoothOfRelativeDimension 1 C.hom] [IsProper C.hom] [GeometricallyIrreducible C.hom]}.
We call such a $C$ a \emph{smooth proper curve over $k$}.

\section{Definition}

\begin{definition}[Genus of a smooth proper curve]
  \label{def:genus}
  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.genus}
  \uses{def:Scheme_HModule, def:Scheme_toModuleKSheaf}
  The \emph{genus} of a smooth proper curve $C$ over $k$ is the natural number
  \[
    g(C) \;=\; \dim_k H^1(C,\, \mathcal O_C),
  \]
  the $k$-dimension of the first sheaf-cohomology group of the structure sheaf of $C$.
\end{definition}

\begin{proof}
  \uses{def:Scheme_HModule, def:Scheme_toModuleKSheaf}
  The Lean implementation expresses this via the project's $\ModuleCat\,k$-flavoured sheaf cohomology of the structure sheaf:
  \[
    \mathtt{genus}\,C \;:=\; \Module.\mathtt{finrank}\,k\,\bigl(\Scheme.\HModule\,k\,(\Scheme.\toModuleKSheaf\,C)\,1\bigr).
  \]
  The carrier $\Scheme.\toModuleKSheaf\,C$ is the iter-006 sheaf-of-$k$-modules constructed from $\struct C$ via the structure morphism $C.\mathrm{hom}$; the wrapper $\Scheme.\HModule\,k\,F\,1$ is the iter-009 $\Module\,k$-flavoured sheaf cohomology, given by $\Ext_{\Sheaf(\opens C, \ModuleCat\,k)}((\mathtt{constantSheaf}\,J\,(\ModuleCat\,k)).\mathrm{obj}\,(\ModuleCat.\mathrm{of}\,k\,k),\, F,\, 1)$, which carries a canonical $\Module\,k$-structure inherited from \lstinline{Abelian.Ext.instModule} (against the $\Linear\,k$-enrichment of $\Sheaf(J, \ModuleCat\,k)$, auto-inferable from \lstinline{HasSheafify}).

  Mathlib's $\Module.\mathtt{finrank}$ returns the $k$-dimension when the underlying module is finite-dimensional and zero otherwise. For a smooth proper geometrically irreducible curve, Serre's theorem on coherent cohomology of a proper $k$-scheme guarantees $\dim_k H^1(C, \struct C) < \infty$, so $g(C)$ is the geometric genus on the relevant case (Serre finiteness is left as Phase A step 6 *proper* and is not invoked at the level of the *definition*). The closure is therefore the one-liner
  \[
    \Module.\mathtt{finrank}\,k\,\bigl(\Scheme.\HModule\,k\,(\Scheme.\toModuleKSheaf\,C)\,1\bigr),
  \]
  probe-confirmed to typecheck against current Mathlib (kernel-only axioms) in the iter-011 plan-agent's \lstinline{lean_run_code} probe.
\end{proof}

Equivalent reformulations available once Riemann–Roch and Serre duality are formalised:
\begin{itemize}
  \item $g(C) = \dim_k H^0(C,\, \Omega^1_{C/k})$ (Serre duality).
  \item $g(C) = 1 - \chi(\mathcal O_C)$, where $\chi$ is the Euler characteristic.
  \item For a smooth projective curve over $\mathbb C$, $g(C)$ equals the topological genus of $C(\mathbb C)$.
\end{itemize}
Each of these requires Mathlib infrastructure that is currently absent. The first reformulation in particular requires the sheaf of relative differentials of schemes (Phase B of \texttt{STRATEGY.md}), and the others require Riemann–Roch / Serre duality / a topological-vs-algebraic geometry comparison (out of project scope for the foreseeable iterations).

\section{Mathlib gap}
\label{sec:Genus_status}

The honest definition $\dim_k H^1(C, \mathcal O_C)$ requires a $\Module\,k$-flavoured sheaf cohomology of $\struct C$ on the topology of opens of $C.\mathrm{left}$. Through iter-010 the project has built this:

\begin{itemize}
  \item \textbf{Sheaf cohomology of $\AddCommGrpCat$-valued sheaves} (\lstinline{CategoryTheory.Sheaf.H}, file \lstinline{Mathlib/CategoryTheory/Sites/SheafCohomology/Basic.lean}, Mathlib): defined as $\Ext$ from the constant sheaf at $\AddCommGrpCat.\mathrm{of}\,(\ULift\,\mathbb Z)$.
  \item \textbf{Sheaf cohomology of $\ModuleCat\,k$-valued sheaves} (\lstinline{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.HModule}, this project, iter-009): the parallel $\Module\,k$-valued construction with unit object $\ModuleCat.\mathrm{of}\,k\,k$ instead of $\ULift\,\mathbb Z$, gluing through the $\Linear\,k$-enrichment of $\Sheaf(J, \ModuleCat\,k)$ to recover a $\Module\,k$ structure on the cohomology groups.
  \item \textbf{Structure sheaf as a $\ModuleCat\,k$-valued sheaf} (\lstinline{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.toModuleKSheaf}, this project, iter-006): for $C : \mathrm{Over}\,(\Spec\,(\CommRingCat\,k))$, the sheafification of the presheaf $U \mapsto \ModuleCat.\mathrm{of}\,k\,(\Gamma(C.\mathrm{left}, U))$ where the $k$-action is the algebra structure induced by the structure morphism $C.\mathrm{hom}$.
  \item \textbf{$H^0$ algebraic bridge} (\lstinline{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.HModule_zero_linearEquiv}, this project, iter-010): $H^0(C, \struct C)_{\Module\,k} \simeq_k \Hom_{\Sheaf(J, \ModuleCat\,k)}((\mathtt{constantSheaf}\dots).\mathrm{obj}\,(\ModuleCat.\mathrm{of}\,k\,k),\, \toModuleKSheaf\,C)$, via Mathlib's \lstinline{Abelian.Ext.linearEquiv₀}. Used downstream for the geometric content $H^0(C, \struct C) \simeq k$ on a connected proper $k$-curve (multi-iteration; iter-012+).
\end{itemize}

The remaining Mathlib gap for the *theorem* (as opposed to the *definition*) of genus:

\begin{itemize}
  \item \textbf{Serre finiteness for $H^i(C, \mathcal F)$ on a proper $k$-curve} (\lstinline{Module.Finite k (HModule k (toModuleKSheaf C) i)} in our setting). Mathlib's \lstinline{ModuleCat.finite_ext} (\lstinline{Mathlib/Algebra/Category/ModuleCat/Ext/Finite.lean}) provides $\Module.\mathtt{Finite}$ for module-Ext only, not sheaf-Ext. Path 2 (Čech-cohomology scaffold; Mathlib's \lstinline{CategoryTheory.cechComplexFunctor} is now available) is the recommended iter-012+ direction.
\end{itemize}

\section{User authorisation of \texttt{noncomputable}}
\label{sec:Genus_noncomputable}

The original \lstinline{references/challenge.lean} writes \lstinline{def genus}, not \lstinline{noncomputable def genus}. Because \lstinline{Module.finrank}, \lstinline{Abelian.Ext.instModule}, and the structure-sheaf-as-$k$-module construction are all noncomputable in Mathlib, the honest closure of the body requires the \lstinline{noncomputable} modifier on the \lstinline{def}. The user (\texttt{2026-05-07}) explicitly authorised agents to add this modifier as a "non-signature change": names, argument types, and argument order remain verbatim. The iter-011 refactor agent therefore changes \lstinline{def genus} to \lstinline{noncomputable def genus} (and imports \lstinline{AlgebraicJacobian.Cohomology.StructureSheafModuleK}); the iter-011 prover round fills the body.

\section{What \emph{this} iteration does and does not}

This (iter-011) iteration *defines* the genus. It does not *compute* it on any specific curve, and it does not prove that the result equals the geometric genus in the classical sense (which requires Serre finiteness for non-vacuity and Riemann–Roch for verification on examples). The downstream theorem \lstinline{smoothOfRelativeDimension_genus} in \lstinline{Jacobian.lean} states $\Jacobian C$ is smooth of relative dimension $\genus C$ — that theorem will require Serre finiteness on the way (because \lstinline{Jacobian C} is a $g(C)$-dimensional scheme) and is queued for the iteration that closes \lstinline{Jacobian C} itself, which is gated on Phase C representability and is multi-iteration upstream work.
